00:18:13.450 --> 00:18:16.180
And to build them
we're looking for help,

00:18:16.180 --> 00:18:20.490
so we're looking to partner
with developers in this space.

00:18:20.490 --> 00:18:22.550
And to this end,
we've launched what

00:18:22.550 --> 00:18:26.850
we're calling the App Incubator
program for Project Tango.

00:18:26.850 --> 00:18:30.590
This is, again, a collaboration
between Google and Lenovo.

00:18:30.590 --> 00:18:32.910
And through this
program we're looking

00:18:32.910 --> 00:18:35.650
for developers and
studios who are

00:18:35.650 --> 00:18:37.990
passionate about
the technology, who

00:18:37.990 --> 00:18:40.100
are passionate about
the space, and who

00:18:40.100 --> 00:18:43.730
have ideas about what they could
build on top of this platform.

00:18:43.730 --> 00:18:47.930
And then Google and Lenovo
will work with these companies

00:18:47.930 --> 00:18:51.510
to provide funding,
to provide supports,

00:18:51.510 --> 00:18:55.190
and to help make your vision
and your dream of what

00:18:55.190 --> 00:18:58.330
you could do with an
application and platform

00:18:58.330 --> 00:19:00.640
like this a reality.

00:19:00.640 --> 00:19:04.080
There will be opportunities
to be featured on the device

00:19:04.080 --> 00:19:07.530
as it launches,
and Lenovo has also

00:19:07.530 --> 00:19:10.940
stated a desire to
have some of these apps

00:19:10.940 --> 00:19:16.050
be preinstalled on the device--
opening up the market that will

00:19:16.050 --> 00:19:18.350
be exposed to your technology.

00:19:18.350 --> 00:19:23.290
And we are accepting
proposals for applications

00:19:23.290 --> 00:19:26.850
through February
15, 2016, so we're

00:19:26.850 --> 00:19:31.590
looking to make decisions as
to what applications we fund

00:19:31.590 --> 00:19:34.540
in the relatively near future.

00:19:34.540 --> 00:19:37.730
You can go to
google.com/projecttango,

00:19:37.730 --> 00:19:41.420
and you'll find more information
on applying for the program.

00:19:41.420 --> 00:19:45.310
So if you have an
idea that you're

00:19:45.310 --> 00:19:48.010
passionate about
for this platform,

00:19:48.010 --> 00:19:50.780
we really, really
want to hear from you.

00:19:50.780 --> 00:19:54.300
We know that this can't
happen without creative input,

00:19:54.300 --> 00:19:57.820
and we know that
we don't have all

00:19:57.820 --> 00:20:03.390
of the great ideas that could be
built on top of this platform.

00:20:03.390 --> 00:20:08.220
I'll conclude by just saying
that we have APIs for C,

00:20:08.220 --> 00:20:12.680
for Java, and we have a
tight integration with Unity.

00:20:12.680 --> 00:20:16.160
And we are also working on
an integration with Unreal

00:20:16.160 --> 00:20:17.260
as well.

00:20:17.260 --> 00:20:20.830
So if you use any
of those programming

00:20:20.830 --> 00:20:24.010
platforms for
Android, Tango should

00:20:24.010 --> 00:20:26.430
be relatively easy to pick up.

00:20:26.430 --> 00:20:29.240
I want to leave some
time for questions,

00:20:29.240 --> 00:20:30.830
so I'll take those now.

00:20:30.830 --> 00:20:34.630
I think I've been told there
are mics up front and one

00:20:34.630 --> 00:20:37.320
in the top, so I'll
take questions.

00:20:37.320 --> 00:20:38.286
Yes.

00:20:38.286 --> 00:20:42.133
AUDIENCE: How accurate is
that IR sensor in Tango?

00:20:42.133 --> 00:20:42.633
[INAUDIBLE].

00:20:47.707 --> 00:20:49.290
EITAN MARDER-EPPSTEIN:
So the question

00:20:49.290 --> 00:20:53.510
was how accurate
is the IR sensor?

00:20:53.510 --> 00:20:57.280
So you don't get direct
access to the infrared camera

00:20:57.280 --> 00:20:58.360
with Tango.

00:20:58.360 --> 00:21:00.640
I can talk about the
accuracy of depth,

00:21:00.640 --> 00:21:04.690
but as far as seeing through
walls-- that's something

00:21:04.690 --> 00:21:06.590
that's a little bit hard to do.

00:21:06.590 --> 00:21:11.550
But the depth is accurate to
about 3% over the distance

00:21:11.550 --> 00:21:12.630
that you measure.

00:21:12.630 --> 00:21:13.950
Does that makes sense?

00:21:13.950 --> 00:21:14.586
OK.

00:21:14.586 --> 00:21:15.086
Yes.

00:21:15.086 --> 00:21:17.644
AUDIENCE: How does it
deal with wacky lighting

00:21:17.644 --> 00:21:21.340
and crazy shadows like
the shadows [INAUDIBLE]?

00:21:21.340 --> 00:21:23.340
EITAN MARDER-EPPSTEIN:
Yeah, so the question was

00:21:23.340 --> 00:21:27.340
how does Tango deal with wacky
lighting, or crazy shadows,

00:21:27.340 --> 00:21:29.630
or changes in the environment?

00:21:29.630 --> 00:21:32.370
I think you saw in the
video Tango working

00:21:32.370 --> 00:21:33.800
in the presence
of a lot of people

00:21:33.800 --> 00:21:35.780
that were all moving around.

00:21:35.780 --> 00:21:38.400
And the device
has the capability

00:21:38.400 --> 00:21:42.430
to recognize what
are dynamic obstacles

00:21:42.430 --> 00:21:44.330
in the scene versus static.

00:21:44.330 --> 00:21:46.280
And as long as it
can see some points

00:21:46.280 --> 00:21:50.450
that it can track over time,
it's able to keep its position.

00:21:50.450 --> 00:21:53.510
Yeah, so if you move in
front of the Tango device,

00:21:53.510 --> 00:21:55.370
you'll actually see
the points on you.

00:21:55.370 --> 00:21:57.650
In that display I
showed, they'll turn red.

00:21:57.650 --> 00:22:00.320
And what that means is,
hey, that is not a thing

00:22:00.320 --> 00:22:01.600
that I should be basing--

00:22:01.600 --> 00:22:03.005
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:22:03.005 --> 00:22:04.130
EITAN MARDER-EPPSTEIN: Yes.

00:22:04.130 --> 00:22:05.260
Yeah.

00:22:05.260 --> 00:22:09.140
And then for lighting the
camera changes its exposure

00:22:09.140 --> 00:22:12.960
based on the lighting to try and
maximize the ability to track.

00:22:12.960 --> 00:22:15.750
And that's the other reason we
have that wide-angle camera.

00:22:15.750 --> 00:22:18.460
We want to see as much
of the world as possible

00:22:18.460 --> 00:22:20.276
because if you take
a narrow-angle camera

00:22:20.276 --> 00:22:21.900
and you walk really
close to that wall,

00:22:21.900 --> 00:22:23.360
you'll just see white.

00:22:23.360 --> 00:22:25.660
But the wide-angle gives
us a very wide field

00:22:25.660 --> 00:22:30.020
of view of the world and helps
the robustness of our system.

00:22:30.020 --> 00:22:33.050
You in the-- yes-- jacket.

00:22:33.050 --> 00:22:33.560
Yeah.

00:22:33.560 --> 00:22:35.035
You'd put your hand down.

00:22:35.035 --> 00:22:37.034
AUDIENCE: So I'm assuming
all this processing is

00:22:37.034 --> 00:22:38.808
happening on the device, right?

00:22:38.808 --> 00:22:41.676
And all you need [INAUDIBLE]?

00:22:46.934 --> 00:22:48.100
EITAN MARDER-EPPSTEIN: Yeah.

00:22:48.100 --> 00:22:51.890
So the question was we assume
that all the processing is

00:22:51.890 --> 00:22:53.680
happening on the device,
which is correct.

00:22:53.680 --> 00:22:56.250
All of the processing is
happening on the device.

00:22:56.250 --> 00:23:00.300
And how easy is it to
develop a simple app?

00:23:00.300 --> 00:23:02.660
So there-- getting up
and running with Tango

00:23:02.660 --> 00:23:05.090
is very, very easy.

00:23:05.090 --> 00:23:07.570
In Unity, it takes
less than 10 minutes

00:23:07.570 --> 00:23:11.910
to have a basic
motion controlled

00:23:11.910 --> 00:23:14.300
camera in a virtual scene.

00:23:14.300 --> 00:23:18.480
In C and Java-- maybe up
that to 30 minutes to an hour

00:23:18.480 --> 00:23:20.760
just to get everything set-up.

00:23:20.760 --> 00:23:25.240
And developers.googl
e.com/projecttango has all

00:23:25.240 --> 00:23:27.470
of the entry points
for our tutorials,

00:23:27.470 --> 00:23:30.270
and I'm also very happy to
talk about that at office hours

00:23:30.270 --> 00:23:31.470
as well.

00:23:31.470 --> 00:23:32.990
You standing in the back.

00:23:32.990 --> 00:23:34.316
Yeah.

00:23:34.316 --> 00:23:36.330
AUDIENCE: So does Google
or any of its partners

00:23:36.330 --> 00:23:42.220
have plans for, say,
planetary scale SLAM

00:23:42.220 --> 00:23:47.047
geospatial database-- sort of
like an Instagram for Tango?

00:23:47.047 --> 00:23:48.630
EITAN MARDER-EPPSTEIN:
So the question

00:23:48.630 --> 00:23:50.700
was does Google have
plans to, I guess,

00:23:50.700 --> 00:23:53.530
map the world with Tango?

00:23:53.530 --> 00:23:55.970
So at Google we're always
interested in mapping

00:23:55.970 --> 00:23:57.130
the world.

00:23:57.130 --> 00:24:00.760
We do think that this technology
has a lot of potential

00:24:00.760 --> 00:24:02.580
for indoor navigation.

00:24:02.580 --> 00:24:06.070
So we've started with some
trials where you go to a mall,

00:24:06.070 --> 00:24:08.660
and you turn on the device,
and you can do things

00:24:08.660 --> 00:24:11.840
like get directed to a store
with turn-by-turn directions.

00:24:11.840 --> 00:24:14.850
I know I could have used this
at CES last week, actually.

00:24:14.850 --> 00:24:18.780
Vegas is not good for
indoor navigation.

00:24:18.780 --> 00:24:20.380
And you can also
do things like try

00:24:20.380 --> 00:24:21.850
and find your
friends because you

00:24:21.850 --> 00:24:23.500
have a shared coordinate frame.

00:24:23.500 --> 00:24:26.250
So it's an exploration
that we're beginning.

00:24:26.250 --> 00:24:30.550
We do think location-based
experiences and navigation

00:24:30.550 --> 00:24:34.000
experiences are
one of the pillars

00:24:34.000 --> 00:24:37.170
that we'll explore
for this technology.

00:24:37.170 --> 00:24:42.015
AUDIENCE: So no Google Maps
integration out of the box?

00:24:42.015 --> 00:24:44.390
EITAN MARDER-EPPSTEIN: I cannot
comment about Google Maps

00:24:44.390 --> 00:24:46.820
integration.

